As one would generally expect, the backing store of most hashsets is little more than a hashmap with zero-sized/no values.<p>In fact, that&#x27;s exactly how Rust&#x27;s standard library hashset is implemented since rust supports zero-sized types &quot;in userland&quot; (and unit `()` is a ZST):<p><pre><code>    pub struct HashSet<T, S = RandomState> {
        map: HashMap<T, (), S>
    }
</code></pre>
<a href="http://doc.rust-lang.org/src/std/collections/hash/set.rs.html#112-114" rel="nofollow">http://doc.rust-lang.org/src/std/collections/hash/set.rs.htm...</a>
